SIMPLE: gulf
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gulf
<hw>Gulf</hw> <pr>(g⟦ucr⟧lf)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>golfe</ets>, It. <ets>golfo</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>ko`lpos</grk>
bosom, bay, gulf, LGr. <grk>ko`lfos</grk>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
hollow place in the earth; an abyss; a deep chasm or basin,</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He then surveyed⟦br⟧
Hell and the <qex>gulf</qex> between.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Between us and you there is a great gulf fixed.</q> <rj><qau>Luke
xvi. 26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which swallows; the gullet.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which swallows irretrievably; a whirlpool; a
sucking eddy.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>gulf</qex> of ruin, swallowing gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>A portion of an ocean or sea
extending into the land; a partially land-locked sea; <as>as, the
<ex>Gulf</ex> of Mexico</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A large deposit of ore in a
lode.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gulf Stream</b></col> <fld>(Geog.)</fld>, <cd>the warm
ocean current of the North Atlantic.</cd> <note>It originates in the
westward equatorial current, due to the trade winds, is deflected
northward by Cape St. Roque through the Gulf of Mexico, and flows
parallel to the coast of North America, turning eastward off the island
of Nantucket. Its average rate of flow is said to be about two miles an
hour. The similar Japan current, or <xex>Kuro-Siwo</xex>, is sometimes
called the <xex>Gulf Stream</xex> of the Pacific.</note> -- <col><b>Gulf
weed</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a branching seaweed
(<spn>Sargassum bacciferum</spn>, or sea grape), having numerous
berrylike air vessels, -- found in the Gulf Stream, in the Sargasso Sea,
and elsewhere.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>gulfweed</ent>⟦br⟧
